snippet.textDisplay: As a British person, I'm so confused about the distinction between a swede, turnip and a rutabaga. Chris first uses 'turnips' which don't look like turnips to me. He then gets hold of a rutabaga which is what I would call a turnip, which falls into the assumption I had that a rutabaga was the american term for what we call a turnip, but they're being referred to as separate things here, and when I check wikipedia for rutabega, it says "rutabaga, neep, turnip, or snagger, also called..." as if they are the same thing. What were the smaller red 'turnips' Chris was using in the beginning?
